---
// src/components/StrategicDeepDive.astro
---
<section class="py-24 bg-slate-50 border-t border-slate-200">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        
        <div class="text-center max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6 tracking-tight text-display">
                Four questions smart owners ask us.
            </h2>
            <p class="text-slate-500 text-lg leading-relaxed">
                You have built a successful business. You are skeptical of "magic bullets." We respect that. Here is the honest truth.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 shadow-sm border border-slate-200 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow flex flex-col">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-purple-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center text-purple-600 mb-6 shrink-0">
                    <i data-lucide="smartphone" class="w-6 h-6"></i>
                </div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4 h-auto md:h-14 flex items-center">
                    "I get all my clients from Instagram. Why do I need a website?"
                </h3>
                <div class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-4">
                    <p>
                        <strong>Social Media is "Attention". Google is "Intention".</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        People scroll Instagram to kill time. They search Google to solve a problem.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-slate-900 font-medium pt-2 border-t border-slate-100">
                        When a client searches "Anxiety Therapy Subang", they are holding their credit card, ready to book. That is the high-intent traffic you are currently missing.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 shadow-sm border border-slate-200 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow flex flex-col">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-yellow-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center text-yellow-600 mb-6 shrink-0">
                    <i data-lucide="star" class="w-6 h-6"></i>
                </div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4 h-auto md:h-14 flex items-center">
                    "I already have 1,000+ Google Reviews. Why do I need this?"
                </h3>
                <div class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-4">
                    <p>
                        <strong>Reviews are your Reputation. Stegg is your Reach.</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Your reviews are amazing, but they are stuck on a "leash." Google Maps prioritizes distance. If a customer is 8km away, Google hides youâ€”no matter how many stars you have.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-slate-900 font-medium pt-2 border-t border-slate-100">
                        Stegg puts you in front of people who are too far for the Map, but willing to travel for quality.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 shadow-sm border border-slate-200 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow flex flex-col">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-blue-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center text-blue-600 mb-6 shrink-0">
                    <i data-lucide="map" class="w-6 h-6"></i>
                </div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4 h-auto md:h-14 flex items-center">
                    "Will this help my Google Map ranking too?"
                </h3>
                <div class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-4">
                    <p>
                        <strong>Yes, absolutely.</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Google looks for "Prominence." When our pages start driving traffic from neighborhoods like <em>Mont Kiara</em> to your site, it sends a signal to Google: <em class="italic">"This business is relevant to that neighborhood."</em>
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-slate-900 font-medium pt-2 border-t border-slate-100">
                        Over time, this organic traffic helps "stretch" your Map radius, helping you rank in the Map Pack further from your HQ.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 shadow-sm border border-slate-200 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow flex flex-col">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center text-green-600 mb-6 shrink-0">
                    <i data-lucide="check-circle-2" class="w-6 h-6"></i>
                </div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4 h-auto md:h-14 flex items-center">
                    "Does this really work? It sounds too simple."
                </h3>
                <div class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-4">
                    <p>
                        <strong>It works because it's boring math.</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Google is a robot. It wants to give the searcher the <em>exact</em> match.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If someone searches "Your Service + Location", and you have a page titled exactly <strong>"Your Service + Location"</strong>, you mathematically beat a competitor who just has a generic "Home" page.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-slate-900 font-medium pt-2 border-t border-slate-100">
                        We just automate the "boring work" of creating those perfect matches.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</section>